description.plain:
Built to Spill is an American indie rock band based in Boise, Idaho, formed in 1992 and led by Doug Martsch, who has also been the only permanent member.

Regarding the band name, Martsch said:

It was a game my wife and I played where we’d take turns writing a word. She’d write a word, then I’d write a word and we’d make up poems and stories. So when I was trying to come up with a band name we went back through them together to see if there was anything interesting and it was a part of that.

description.plain: Big Dipper follows the speaker reminiscing about the sense of wonder they had as a child. As an adult, they spend their time coasting through life, uninterested in much of anything. When looking up at the big dipper as a child, they viewed it as a brontosaurus and was amazed by the sight. In an attempt to regain that feeling of wonder, they drink and look up at the sky only to see it as the big dipper and not the brontosaurus.

body.plain:
“Life’s a Dream” is the fifth track on Built to Spill’s most recent album, There is No Enemy. The album is the last to feature Scott Plouf (bass) and Brett Nelson (drums), who retired from the band in 2012.

The song is about the challenges of human life, and the traps of human perspective on the values of living in the moment. It addresses the idea that maybe we are living in a dream, and we are too scared to wake up to reality.

description.plain:
The first song on Build to Spill’s 1997 album Perfect From Now On, “Randy Described Eternity” is, as its title succinctly states, a poetic description of eternity as told to lead singer/lyricist Doug Martsch by the leader of his Christian youth group. In a blog post, a fan estimated that it would take 1.125 x 1037 years to perform the feat this song describes.

Speaking of extremely long lengths of time, “Randy Describes Eternity” kicks off Perfect From Now On’s consistently long songs, all of which are between (slightly under) five and nine minutes long.

songs.title: The Source

description.plain: The Source continues the apathetic tone of previous songs on the record. The first verse showing the apathy the speaker has for living by sharing his morning routine. Yet he incessantly ask the audience what makes them feel so bad and why it makes them feel that way. The answer, the speaker suggests, is the source. The source can be interpreted as many different things, such as the human condition or life itself. In the end it’s left for the listener to decide.

description.plain: This is the second song on Built to Spill’s first album, Ultimate Alternative Wavers (1993 C/Z Records). Putting it at the beginning shows how much it meant to the lead singer, Doug Martsch. This whole song is about how Doug had to watch his beloved cat suffer for a month and die. Even cat haters can respect the love he had for his friend. This is a passionate, emotional song, both lyrically and musically.

songs.title: Twin Falls

description.plain:
The eighth song on Built to Spill’s album is about an idealized childhood love.

Although the narrator of the song moved away from Twin Falls when he was young and appears never to have seen her again, he still thinks—and even dreams—about her.

Doug Martsch, the frontman for Built to Spill, did grow up in Twin Falls, so it’s possible that there are some autobiographical elements in the song.
